{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_011SgBjFH7uWbmyUyehNCfED","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see! The pod `rabbitmq-2` is STILL running the `rabbitmq:4.1-management` image (version 4.1.8). The patch to 3.13 hasn't taken effect yet! The StatefulSet rolling update is stuck because rabbitmq-2 hasn't become ready, so the StatefulSet controller won't terminate and restart it with the new image.\n\nIn StatefulSets with `OrderedReady` pod management policy:\n- It tries to update pods from the highest ordinal to the lowest\n- It won't proceed to the next pod until the current one is Ready\n- rabbitmq-2 is stuck not-ready, so the controller is waiting for it to become ready before terminating and re-creating it with 3.13\n\nBut here's the catch: rabbitmq-2 is running 4.1 and can't join the 3.12 cluster, so it will never become ready. I'm caught in a deadlock where the StatefulSet won't re-create the pod with the new image because it's waiting for the old pod to become ready first.\n\nTo break out of this, I could manually delete the rabbitmq-2 pod and let the StatefulSet recreate it with the current desired image. But wait—I just patched to 3.13-management, yet the pod is still running 4.1 because the rolling update is stuck waiting for readiness with the old image. Let me trace through what actually happened: the StatefulSet went from 3.12 to 4.1 to 3.13 across patches, and now I need to figure out which revision is actually the desired state.\n\nThe StatefulSet controller should be trying to update rabbitmq-2 to 3.13 now, but it's still running 4.1. When I patched to 3.13, the controller should have seen that rabbitmq-2 doesn't match the current desired revision and terminated it to recreate it with the new spec. With the default RollingUpdate strategy, pods are updated one at a time from highest to lowest ordinal, and the controller waits for each pod to be Running and Ready before moving on