{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01XbvDj53KisyDa9qTk5CYen","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The logs don't give me the specific flags that are incompatible. Let me try to look at the early boot sequence of rabbitmq-2 to see if there are any debug messages about which feature flags are specifically incompatible. Or let me try a different approach.\n\nActually, I know the core issue:\n- RabbitMQ 4.1 (and probably 3.13) has new feature flags that 3.12 doesn't support\n- A standard rolling upgrade fails because of this\n\nThe correct approach for this type of upgrade is what RabbitMQ calls a \"blue-green\" deployment or what they alternatively call a \"full cluster upgrade\":\nI need to export the queue definitions and messages via the Management API, then scale the StatefulSet to zero and delete the stuck pod to get a clean slate. After that, I'll scale back up with the 4.1 image so all nodes start fresh as a new cluster, then reimport the definitions and messages.\n\nActually, there's a better way to think about this. Since all nodes have mirrored data, I could scale everything to zero first, which clears the emptyDir storage, then scale back up with the 4.1 image to form a fresh cluster. The tradeoff is losing queued messages temporarily, but I can restore them afterward—though that conflicts with the requirement to preserve existing queue data.\n\nLet me reconsider a smarter approach where I back up the messages first using the Management HTTP API before doing the full restart. I realize the messages won't survive pod restarts since they're on emptyDir, but the HA mirroring keeps them safe as long as one node stays up. I'm going to execute the plan using `kubectl exec` to access `rabbitmqadmin` from within the cluster—I can extract the queue definitions and messages, perform the upgrade, then restore everything afterward. Let me think through the startup sequence to make sure this works cleanly.\n\nActually, I'm noticing the real issue now: rabbitmq-2 is stuck in a startup probe failure loop. The StatefulSet is in a deadlock where rabbitmq-2 was already rolled to 4.1.8 during the previous upgrade attempt, but it's not becoming ready, so the controller can't proceed. Now that I've changed the target image to 3.13-management, the StatefulSet is confused about what state it should be in.\n\nThe straightforward fix would be to delete the rabbitmq-2 pod so the StatefulSet recreates it with the correct 3.13 image, but that only works if 3.13 can actually join the existing 3.12 cluster without hitting the same feature flag compatibility issue. Let me reconsider the approach entirely.\n\nSince we're working with non-persistent emptyDir storage, the data only survives as long as the pods are running, and HA mirroring requires at least one node alive to preserve it. A rolling upgrade won't work due to feature flag incompatibility, so I need to export the queue messages and cluster definitions first, then do an all-at-once upgrade by scaling down to zero, deleting the stuck pod, and scaling back up with the new image.\n\nI'll use the RabbitMQ Management API through kubectl exec to export the messages without consuming them, then re-publish them to the new cluster once it's running. The specific message content matters less than preserving the message bodies and delivery semantics.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4244,"cache_read_input_tokens":64841,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4244},"output_tokens":19,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9428bb29-e5b2-4a20-b8cb-0b98077d2c13","uuid":"58390e13-29d1-44a5-b0e8-7492e3dd8802","request_id":"req_011CcdeYrudaUUjbLs67zQ4W"}
