{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01NBGLdgxxzf6ypV8rGtxnUE","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK so the messages are simple text messages. I can see \"msg-1\", \"msg-2\", \"msg-3\", then \"app-msg-0\", \"app-msg-1\", etc.\n\nNow I need to save ALL messages so I can re-publish them after the upgrade. But with 710+ messages, I can't do this manually. \n\nLet me write a Python script inside the container to:\n1. Get all messages from the queue (using the Management HTTP API)\n2. Save them to a file\n3. After upgrading, re-publish them\n\nActually, I can do this differently. The definition export already captures the queue definition and policies. \n\nI need to think through the full sequence: save the definitions, extract all the messages, upgrade the broker, restore the definitions, then republish the messages. For the message extraction, I'll write a script that hits the Management API to pull messages with the requeue flag set, then persist them to JSON. The tricky part is handling the ongoing message production from the app-client while I'm trying to capture everything. all the messages are actually persisted in the queue itself, so I don't need to worry about app-client buffering. The real plan is to pause app-client during the upgrade window, export the queue contents, perform the upgrade, and then restore everything—but I should verify whether stopping the app is actually necessary or if I can just let it fail gracefully during the maintenance window.\n\nWriting Python script to export messages... Writing the output script...","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":497,"cache_read_input_tokens":73759,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":497},"output_tokens":24,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_manageme