{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01XVUKE5iNT8pZJJsrDGDALD","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"All 727 messages have empty payloads! This is clearly wrong since the messages should contain strings like \"msg-1\", \"msg-2\", \"app-msg-0\", etc. (5 bytes each, which matches the payload_bytes).\n\nLet me think about why this is happening...\n\nPossible explanations:\n1. The messages were already consumed by the `ack_requeue_true` call and re-queued as empty messages (lost payload on requeue)\n2. There's a bug with how the Management API returns peeked messages when the payload is small or in certain conditions\n3. The messages could be corrupted\n\nActually, I think I see what happened. When I ran that earlier command with `ack_requeue_true`, it consumed and requeued the messages, but the management plugin might not be preserving payloads properly during the requeue operation. Or there's something odd with the JSON encoding—the payload_bytes shows 5, which would be right for \"msg-1\", but the payload field is empty. I'm wondering if there's truncation happening somewhere.\n\nLooking back at my Python script, I set `'truncate': 0` in the request parameters. According to the RabbitMQ docs, that parameter controls whether message payloads larger than a certain byte threshold get truncated—and setting it to 0 would truncate everything to 0 bytes. That's likely the culprit. I need to either omit that parameter or set it to a large value like 50000 to see the full payloads.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1374,"cache_read_input_tokens":77092,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1374},"output_tokens":28,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9428bb29-e5b2-