{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01CBKBvf7U9kxHe1BhBVPuCP","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The curl-test pod has curl and can reach the RabbitMQ Management API. \n\nNow I need to:\n1. Import definitions via Management API\n2. Re-publish messages via Management API\n\nFor importing definitions, I need to:\n- Upload the definitions JSON to the Management API\n\nBut I need to get the definitions file to the curl-test pod first. Let me copy it there.\n\nActually, I can just pipe the definitions directly to the API without copying the file:\n\n```bash\nkubectl -n $NS exec -i curl-test -- curl -s -u admin:adminpass -X POST -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" http://rabbitmq:15672/api/definitions -d @- < /tmp/rmq-definitions.json\n```\n\nFor re-publishing messages, I need to read them from the JSON file and publish each one via the Management API's publish endpoint. The endpoint format is `POST /api/exchanges/{vhost}/{exchange}/publish`, so for the default exchange in the app vhost, I'd use either the empty exchange name or `amq.default`.\n\nThe API expects a JSON payload with the message properties, routing key, and the actual message content. I'm thinking through whether to use a bash script with curl or a Python script—since I don't have direct access to the cluster's Management API from the host, I'll need to either use `kubectl exec` to run curl commands inside the container, or set up port forwarding to access the API locally.\n\nPort forwarding seems cleaner—I can run `kubectl port-forward` in the background to expose the Management API on localhost, then use Python to import the definitions and publish all the messages through that tunnel.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2537,"cache_read_input_tokens":84420,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":