{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_013VUxH4Sh19WWRzwUjJdiLi","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Hmm, the messages now have additional headers `x-delivery-count` because they're in a quorum queue (quorum queues track delivery counts). The format is different from before.\n\nLooking at the output:\n```\n5   true    app-queue  1491  delivery_mode: 2,headers: {\"x-delivery-count\":2},  msg-1       string \n```\n\nFields separated by whitespace:\n1. `5` (payload_bytes)\n2. `true` (redelivered)\n3. `app-queue` (routing_key)\n4. `1491` (message_count)\n5. `delivery_mode: 2,headers: {\"x-delivery-count\":2},` (properties with headers embedded)\n6. `msg-1` (payload)\n7. `string` (encoding)\n\nSo using NF-2 to get the payload should work since the headers are embedded in the properties field. Let me verify the exact format of that delivery count header to make sure I'm parsing it correctly. I'm realizing that the `x-delivery-count` header value doesn't affect the field count since the JSON object stays as a single field regardless of whether it's `{\"x-delivery-count\":2}` or `{\"x-delivery-count\":10}`. So using `$(NF-1)` should consistently extract the message ID across all entries. So messages republished to the quorum queue without special properties should have a consistent format, but when peeked multiple times with `ack_requeue_true`, RabbitMQ 4.1 adds the `x-delivery-count` header dynamically. I need to account for both cases—messages with and without that header—when extracting the payload field. Let me recount the fields more carefully. Without x-delivery-count, I get 8 fields total with NF-1 pointing to msg-1, which is the payload. With x-delivery-count included, the field count goes up but msg-1 still ends up at NF-1, confirming that's the reliable way to extract the message regardless of headers.\n\nI'm realizing the awk approach is getting tangled up in shell escaping issues. Instead of fighting with that, I should step back—I already have the original 737 messages saved to a file, so the simpler path is to delete the quorum queue using the proper 4.1 syntax, recreate it as a classic queue, and republish those saved messages. The additional 755 messages can be handled separately once the queue is fixed.\n\nNow I need to figure out the exact rabbitmqadmin commands for 4.1 to delete and declare the queue.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":555,"cache_read_input_tokens":110015,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":555},"output_tokens":26,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9428bb29-e5b2-4a20-b8cb-0b98077d2c13","uuid":"bc3f9c2a-55b5-47a5-8dbb-ce15f20a418c","request_id":"req_011Ccdfno3iSfkYVBjit9t8r"}
