{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_014DiCudKrjWuDoDTA4G8VEm","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The upgrade is complete. Here's a summary of what was accomplished:\n\n## Upgrade Summary: RabbitMQ 3.12 → 4.1\n\n**Result: All requirements met.**\n\n| Requirement | Status |\n|-------------|--------|\n| All 3 nodes on RabbitMQ 4.1 | ✅ 4.1.8 on Erlang 27.3.4.13 |\n| /app vhost exists | ✅ |\n| app-queue exists with messages | ✅ 760 messages (growing) |\n| Cluster healthy, 3 nodes | ✅ No alarms, no partitions |\n\n**What happened and why:**\n\n- A direct rolling upgrade from 3.12 → 4.1 fails because RabbitMQ 4.x introduces mandatory feature flags unknown to 3.12 — new pods refused to join the existing cluster (`incompatible_feature_flags`).\n\n- The solution was a **blue-green upgrade**:\n  1. Exported all 737 queue messages and cluster definitions while 3.12 was healthy\n  2. Scaled the StatefulSet to 0 (all nodes down simultaneously)\n  3. Set image to `rabbitmq:4.1-management` and scaled back to 3 — all nodes came up on the same version, forming a fresh 4.1 cluster with no incompatibility check\n  4. Restored users, vhosts, and permissions via the import API\n  5. Recreated app-queue as a classic durable queue (RabbitMQ 4.0 removed the classic HA mirroring policy that the old setup used)\n  6. Republished all 737 original messages"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1036,"cache_read_input_tokens":117536,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1036},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9428bb29-e5b2-4a20-b8cb-0b98077d2c13","uuid":"f39e2ab2-8702-4661-bd76-b4368ec3683d","request_id":"req_011CcdfxyssC1WEERRmnFY7T"}
